elements.content: To determine the influence of metal ions on the formation of metal−organic frameworks, five new coordination polymers, [Pb6(dpa)4O2] n (1), [Ag2(dpa)] n (2), [Nd2(dpa)3(H2O)2] n (3), [Zn(dpa)(H2O)] n (4), and [Cd2(dpa)2(phen)2(H2O)2] n (5), have been hydrothermally synthesized from 1,1‘-biphenyl-2,2‘-dicarboxylate acid (dpa). Complex 1 is a one-dimensional chain structure constructed from a new building unit, Pb6O18, which is connected by four different dpa molecules. Complex 3 is also a one-dimensional chain structure but is composed of a different building unit bridged by three dpa molecules. This complex is further extended into a two-dimensional supramolecular framework. Like complex 3, complex 4 is a two-dimensional supramolecular framework, which is connected by one-dimensional chains through π−π interactions and hydrogen bonding interactions. Complex 5 is a three-dimensional metal−organic supramolecular coordination polymer that possesses rectangular cavities. Different from the above four complexes, complex 2 is a two-dimensional covalence structure. To our knowledge, this is the first two-dimensional coordination polymer composed of metal ions and the dpa ligand. Furthermore, at room temperature, complex 4 exhibits strong photoluminescence.

Introduction

The rational design and syntheses of metal-organic frameworks have been of increasing interest recently in materials science and chemical research since they may provide a new strategy for achieving solid functional materials with potential applications in magnetism, ion exchange, catalysis, gas absorption/separation, and electric conductivity. One of the obvious challenges is the rational and controllable preparation of metal-organic frameworks, the formation of which is greatly affected by the organic ligands, the nature of the metal ions, counterions, and other factors. From the viewpoint of crystal engineering, the most effective and facile approach to overcome this is the appropriate choice of the well-designed organic bridging ligands containing modifiable backbones and connectivity information, together with the metal centers with various coordination preferences. Multidentate N or O donor ligands have been employed extensively as organic spacers in the construction of extended structures, such as 4,4‘-bipyridyl (4,4‘-bpy), pyrazine, 1,4-benzenedicarboxylate, and 1,3,5-benzenetricarboxylate. Among them, the series of biphenyl acid derivatives with adjustable lengths and binding modes attract considerable interest for the modular assembly of metal-organic frameworks, as potential optical and gas absorption materials. Significantly, far less common has been the investigation of related hybrid biphenyl acid linkers with a flexible backbone in the construction of metal-organic frameworks, which do not readily fit into a predictable template due to their structural flexibility and conformational freedom.

elements.content: Recently, research suggests that 2,2‘-biphenyldicarboxylate (dpa) has a strong capability of affording new coordination polymers for several reasons:  (a) The distortion of the diphenyl spacer from the central bond endows dpa a peculiar characterization to link metal ions or metal clusters into macrocycles or helical chains. (b) The 2,2‘-biphenyldicarboxylate ligand contains two bridging moieties, which can lead to a variety of connection modes with metal centers and provides abundant structural motifs. (c) It can act not only as hydrogen bond donors but as acceptors, which make it a wonderful candidate for the construction of supramolecular networks. However, it is interesting that in all dpa-containing structures, only a few simple coordination modes are detected, although a variety of binding fashions are anticipated in metal−organic frameworks under appropriate conditions. To determine the effect of metal ions on the formation of this interesting system, as well as enrich it, metal ions with various characters should be introduced. As we all know, d10 transition metal ions, such as Zn(II) and Cd(II), can produce a variety of complexes that not only exhibit appealing structures but also possess photoluminescence properties. Compared with them, Ag(I) has lower coordination numbers, but the Ag(I)···Ag(I) short contact can also result in some novel and high-dimensional structures. Among those from the lanthanide series, Nd(III) has a larger atom radius and higher coordination numbers than Zn(II), Cd(II), and Ag(I), which allow it to lead to some attractive structures. Pb(II) has different coordination properties and connection modes from the above four kinds of ions. To our knowledge, coordination polymers constructed from Pb(II) are less synthesized and researched. For the above-mentioned reasons, we chose typical Zn(II) and Cd(II) ions and larger Ag(I), Pb(II), and Nd(III) centers with distinct coordination preferences to assemble with the dpa ligand. In this article, five new coordination polymers, [Pb6(dpa)4O2] n (1), [Ag2(dpa)] n (2), [Nd2(dpa)3(H2O)2] n (3), [Zn(dpa)(H2O)] n (4), and [Cd2(dpa)2(phen)2(H2O)2] n (5), were prepared and investigated to determine the influence of metal ions on the formation of such metal−organic frameworks. Interestingly, by careful choice of the metal centers, this series of polymeric networks exhibit varied structural features and binding modes of the dpa ligand.

elements.content: Materials and Methods. All chemicals purchased were of reagent grade and were used without further purification. Elemental analyses (C, N, and H) were performed on a Perkin-Elemer 2400 CHN elemental analyzer. FT/IR spectra were recorded in the range 4000−400 cm-1 on an Alpha Centaut FTIR spectrophotometer using a KBr pellet. Thermogravimetric (TG) analyses were performed on Perkin-Elmer TGA7 instrument in flowing N2 with a heating rate of 10 °C min-1. Photoluminescence spectra were measured using a FL-2T2 instrument (SPEX) with 450-W xenon lamp monochromatized by double grating (1200 gr/mu). All measurements were performed at room temperature.

 Materials and Methods. All chemicals purchased were of reagent grade and were used without further purification. Crystallographic data for 1−5 were all collected at 298 K with a Rigaku R-axis Rapid IP diffractometer using graphite monochromatic Mo Kα radiation (λ = 0.710373 Å) and IP technique. The structure was solved by the direct method and refined by the full-matrix least-squares method on F 2 using the SHELXTL-97 crystallographic software package. Anisotropic thermal parameters were used to refine all non-hydrogen atoms. Carbon-bound hydrogen atoms were placed in geometrically calculated positions; oxygen-bound hydrogen atoms were located in the difference Fourier maps and kept in that position. Crystal data and structure refinement, atomic coordinates, bond lengths and angles, and anisotropic displacement parameters are available in supplementary crystallographic data (Supporting Information, Tables S1−S25).

Conclusion

In this paper, we successfully combined the merits of the dpa ligand and different metal ions to synthesize five coordination polymers with different architecture. Comparing the  structures of the five complexes, we found that the introduction of ions with different coordination ability and modes may have significant effects on the formation and dimension of the resulting structure. The successful preparation of the five different complexes provides a valuable approach for the construction of other coordination polymers with different structures via the introduction of various metal ions. Furthermore, the strong fluorescent properties of complex 4 may make it an excellent candidate for potential photoactive materials.
